\centerline{\bbf File System Organization}

{\ltt{}/bin}, {\ltt{}/usr/bin}--executables

{\ltt{}/sbin}, {\ltt{}/usr/sbin}--executables for admin

{\ltt{}/lib}--libraries (dynamically loaded)

{\ltt{}/etc}--configuration, administration and control files

{\ltt{}/dev}--device controller interface

{\ltt{}/var}--files that grow or vary in size
(print spool, log files).

{\ltt{}/homes}--user home directories

{\ltt{}/tmp}--scratch space

{\ltt{}/}--the base of the file system.

{\ltt{}/boot}--The kernel and other boot-time items

{\ltt{}/root}--the home directory of the admin (root)

{\ltt{}/proc}--a window into the kernel, not a real file system.
information about the kernel appears to be in files and directories

{\ltt{}/sys}--a window into the hardware.

links: a redirection to another place in the tree
\break
{\ltt{}/usr/spool -> /var/spool/}
\qquad (compatibility)
\bye

